{
  "Translation takes place on which cellular structure?": "",
  "Mitochondria": "",
  "Ribosome": "",
  "Nucleus": "",
  "Golgi apparatus": "",
  "Translation occurs on ribosomes, which can be found free in the cytoplasm or bound to the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Ribosomes catalyze peptide bond formation between amino acids.": "",
  "The start codon (AUG) codes for which amino acid?": "",
  "Alanine": "",
  "Leucine": "",
  "Tryptophan": "",
  "Methionine": "",
  "AUG is the universal start codon and codes for methionine (Met). It sets the reading frame for the mRNA and is recognized by a special initiator tRNA that brings the first amino acid to the ribosome.": "",
  "Which molecule serves as an adapter between the mRNA codon and the amino acid during translation?": "",
  "mRNA": "",
  "snRNA": "",
  "tRNA": "",
  "rRNA": "",
  "Transfer RNA (tRNA) is the adapter molecule with an anticodon that pairs with an mRNA codon and carries the corresponding amino acid. Each tRNA is charged with its specific amino acid by an aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzyme.": "",
  "During elongation, a new amino acid is added to the growing polypeptide at which ribosomal site?": "",
  "P (peptidyl) site": "",
  "S (start) site": "",
  "A (aminoacyl) site": "",
  "E (exit) site": "",
  "During elongation, an aminoacyl-tRNA carrying a new amino acid enters the ribosome's A site, where its anticodon is matched with the mRNA codon. A peptide bond is then formed between the new amino acid and the growing chain at the P site.": "",
  "Translation terminates when the ribosome encounters:": "",
  "A stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA)": "",
  "An AUG codon": "",
  "A terminator sequence in the DNA": "",
  "The poly-A tail of the mRNA": "",
  "Translation ends when the ribosome reaches a stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA) in the mRNA. No tRNA has an anticodon for stop codons; instead, release factors bind and trigger the release of the polypeptide.": "",
  "The 'wobble' hypothesis explains why:": "",
  "Ribosomes sometimes skip codons during translation": "",
  "Different organisms use different genetic codes": "",
  "The third position of a codon can tolerate non-standard base pairing, allowing one tRNA to recognize more than one codon": "",
  "Stop codons are sometimes read as amino acids": "",
  "The wobble hypothesis states that the third base of a codon (3' end) and the first base of the anticodon can form non-standard base pairs (wobble pairs). This allows a single tRNA to read more than one codon, which is why fewer than 61 tRNAs are needed.": "",
  "How many nucleotides make up a codon?": "",
  "1": "",
  "3": "",
  "4": "",
  "2": "",
  "A codon consists of three consecutive nucleotides (a triplet) in mRNA that specifies a particular amino acid or a stop signal. There are 64 possible codons (4^3), encoding 20 amino acids and 3 stop signals.": "",
  "Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases are important because they:": "",
  "Break down tRNA after it exits the ribosome": "",
  "Attach the correct amino acid to its corresponding tRNA, ensuring accuracy of translation": "",
  "Synthesize new tRNA molecules from DNA templates": "",
  "Catalyze peptide bond formation on the ribosome": "",
  "Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases are a family of enzymes (one for each amino acid) that specifically recognize both the amino acid and its corresponding tRNA. They catalyze the attachment of the amino acid to the correct tRNA, which is critical for translation accuracy.": "",
  "A polyribosome (polysome) is:": "",
  "A cluster of mRNA molecules waiting to be translated": "",
  "A ribosome composed of multiple large subunits": "",
  "A type of RNA that forms the structural core of the ribosome": "",
  "Multiple ribosomes simultaneously translating the same mRNA molecule": "",
  "A polyribosome (polysome) consists of multiple ribosomes attached to and translating the same mRNA simultaneously. This allows the cell to produce many copies of the same protein efficiently.": "",
  "The peptidyl transferase activity that catalyzes peptide bond formation is a property of:": "",
  "The rRNA component of the large ribosomal subunit (a ribozyme)": "",
  "A protein enzyme in the ribosome": "",
  "tRNA molecules": "",
  "Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase": "",
  "Peptidyl transferase activity is catalyzed by rRNA in the large ribosomal subunit, making the ribosome a ribozyme (RNA enzyme). This discovery was important evidence supporting the RNA World hypothesis.": "",
  "What is 'translation' in molecular biology?": "",
  "The process by which the nucleotide sequence of mRNA is decoded by ribosomes to synthesize a specific polypeptide (protein)": "",
  "The synthesis of RNA from a DNA template": "",
  "The movement of proteins through the Golgi apparatus": "",
  "The replication of DNA before cell division": "",
  "Translation is the second step of gene expression, where the nucleotide sequence of mRNA is 'translated' into an amino acid sequence by ribosomes. Each mRNA codon is matched to a specific amino acid via tRNA adapter molecules.": "",
  "What does 'codon' mean?": "",
  "A segment of DNA that encodes one complete protein": "",
  "A sequence of three consecutive nucleotides in mRNA that specifies a particular amino acid or a stop signal during translation": "",
  "A three-nucleotide sequence on tRNA that pairs with the mRNA": "",
  "The bond between two amino acids in a polypeptide": "",
  "A codon is a triplet of three nucleotides in mRNA that specifies one of the 20 amino acids or signals the termination of translation. The genetic code consists of 64 codons: 61 sense codons for amino acids and 3 stop codons.": "",
  "What is an 'anticodon'?": "",
  "A codon that codes for more than one amino acid": "",
  "A stop signal in the mRNA that terminates translation": "",
  "A three-nucleotide sequence on tRNA that is complementary to an mRNA codon and ensures the correct amino acid is added during translation": "",
  "The region of the ribosome where peptide bonds are formed": "",
  "The anticodon is a three-nucleotide sequence at one end of a tRNA molecule that is complementary to a specific mRNA codon. Base pairing between the codon and anticodon ensures that the correct amino acid is incorporated into the growing polypeptide.": "",
  "What does 'reading frame' mean?": "",
  "The physical frame of the ribosome that holds the mRNA in place": "",
  "The direction in which RNA polymerase reads the DNA template": "",
  "The way in which the sequence of nucleotides in mRNA is grouped into consecutive, non-overlapping triplets (codons) starting from a specific position": "",
  "A set of instructions for operating laboratory sequencing equipment": "",
  "The reading frame is determined by where the ribosome begins reading triplets. The start codon (AUG) sets the reading frame. Any mRNA has three possible reading frames, but only the one initiated at the correct start codon produces the intended protein.": "",
  "What is 'degeneracy' of the genetic code?": "",
  "Different organisms use completely different genetic codes": "",
  "The property that most amino acids are specified by more than one codon, providing redundancy in the genetic code": "",
  "Each codon specifies more than one amino acid": "",
  "The genetic code is deteriorating over evolutionary time": "",
  "Degeneracy (redundancy) means that most amino acids are encoded by two or more codons. For example, leucine is encoded by six different codons. This redundancy provides a buffer against mutations, as some nucleotide changes do not alter the amino acid.": "",
  "What is a 'release factor'?": "",
  "An enzyme that releases tRNA from aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase": "",
  "A factor that releases RNA polymerase from the promoter": "",
  "A protein that recognizes a stop codon in the A site of the ribosome and triggers the release of the completed polypeptide": "",
  "An enzyme that releases mRNA from the ribosome after the first round of translation": "",
  "Release factors are proteins that bind to the ribosomal A site when a stop codon is encountered. They mimic the shape of tRNA and trigger hydrolysis of the bond between the polypeptide and the tRNA in the P site, releasing the completed polypeptide.": "",
  "What does 'peptide bond' mean?": "",
  "The bond between a codon and an anticodon, since the relevant bond factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "A covalent bond formed between the amino group of one amino acid and the carboxyl group of another during translation, linking amino acids in a polypeptide chain": "",
  "The bond between tRNA and its amino acid, particularly when bond considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "A hydrogen bond between two nucleotides in mRNA regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "A peptide bond is a covalent bond formed by a dehydration reaction between the carboxyl group (-COOH) of one amino acid and the amino group (-NH2) of the next. Peptide bond formation is catalyzed by the ribosome during translation.": "",
  "What is a 'ribosome'?": "",
  "An organelle that synthesizes RNA from DNA": "",
  "A complex of rRNA and proteins that serves as the site of translation, reading mRNA codons and catalyzing peptide bond formation": "",
  "A type of transfer RNA that carries amino acids": "",
  "A membrane-bound organelle that processes and packages proteins": "",
  "A ribosome is a macromolecular machine made of rRNA and proteins, consisting of a large subunit and a small subunit. It reads mRNA codons, facilitates tRNA-codon matching, and catalyzes peptide bond formation to build polypeptide chains.": "",
  "What does 'central dogma' mean in molecular biology?": "",
  "The principle that genetic information flows from DNA to RNA to protein, describing the fundamental direction of information transfer in cells": "",
  "The observation that all life uses the same 20 amino acids": "",
  "The rule that all organisms share the same number of genes": "",
  "The hypothesis that proteins can be converted back into DNA": "",
  "The central dogma of molecular biology, proposed by Francis Crick, states that genetic information generally flows from DNA (replication) to RNA (transcription) to protein (translation). While exceptions exist (e.g., reverse transcription), this remains the fundamental framework.": "",
  "What is 'post-translational modification'?": "",
  "Chemical modifications made to a protein after it has been translated, such as phosphorylation, glycosylation, or cleavage, that affect its function, location, or activity": "",
  "The splicing of introns from pre-mRNA, which is consistent with how post mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The addition of a poly-A tail to mRNA after transcription within the broader context of post analysis": "",
  "Modifications to DNA after replication, since standard models of post behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Post-translational modifications are chemical changes made to proteins after synthesis. These include phosphorylation, glycosylation, acetylation, ubiquitination, and proteolytic cleavage. They regulate protein activity, stability, localization, and interactions.": "",
  "A molecular biologist discovers that a patient has a mutation in a gene encoding an aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase that specifically charges tRNA-Phe with phenylalanine. The mutation causes the enzyme to occasionally attach leucine instead. What would be the consequence?": "",
  "The mRNA codons for phenylalanine would be changed to leucine codons": "",
  "All proteins in the cell would be completely degraded": "",
  "tRNA-Phe would no longer be able to enter the ribosome": "",
  "Some proteins would have leucine substituted for phenylalanine at various positions, potentially causing misfolded and nonfunctional proteins": "",
  "If the synthetase incorrectly charges tRNA-Phe with leucine, the ribosome would incorporate leucine wherever a Phe codon appears. The ribosome cannot distinguish the amino acid; it only checks the codon-anticodon match. This would produce misfolded proteins with leucine in place of phenylalanine.": "",
  "Antibiotics like tetracycline and chloramphenicol target bacterial ribosomes but do not affect human cytoplasmic ribosomes. Why can these antibiotics selectively kill bacteria without harming human cells?": "",
  "Human cells do not perform translation": "",
  "Bacteria do not use ribosomes for protein synthesis": "",
  "Bacterial ribosomes (70S) are structurally different from eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosomes (80S), so the antibiotics bind specifically to bacterial ribosomes": "",
  "The antibiotics are degraded by human enzymes before they can reach the ribosomes": "",
  "Bacterial ribosomes (70S, with 30S and 50S subunits) differ structurally from eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosomes (80S, with 40S and 60S subunits). Antibiotics exploit these differences to selectively bind and inhibit bacterial ribosomes without affecting human protein synthesis.": "",
  "The genetic code is described as 'nearly universal.' A student learns that some organisms, like certain mitochondria, use slightly different codon assignments. What is the evolutionary significance of the genetic code being nearly universal?": "",
  "It proves that all organisms were created independently with the same code": "",
  "It demonstrates that organisms cannot evolve new genetic codes": "",
  "It shows that the genetic code was designed for maximum efficiency": "",
  "It provides strong evidence that all life on Earth shares a common ancestor that used this same genetic code": "",
  "The near-universality of the genetic code is powerful evidence for common ancestry. All known life (with minor exceptions) uses the same codon-amino acid assignments, suggesting this code was established in the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) and has been conserved ever since.": "",
  "A researcher uses puromycin, a drug that resembles a charged tRNA. Puromycin enters the ribosomal A site and forms a peptide bond with the growing chain, but cannot undergo translocation. What effect does puromycin have on translation?": "",
  "It causes premature termination by blocking further elongation, releasing truncated polypeptides": "",
  "It prevents initiation by blocking the start codon": "",
  "It has no effect because the ribosome can distinguish it from real tRNA": "",
  "It speeds up translation by providing extra amino acids": "",
  "Puromycin mimics aminoacyl-tRNA and enters the A site, forming a peptide bond with the nascent chain. However, the puromycin-peptide conjugate cannot be translocated, so it is released as a truncated polypeptide, prematurely terminating translation.": "",
  "A biotechnology company engineers bacteria to produce human insulin. The human insulin gene is placed after a bacterial promoter, and the bacteria successfully transcribe and translate the gene. However, the insulin protein does not fold correctly and is inactive. What additional step is likely needed?": "",
  "The bacteria need to replicate the insulin gene more times, as conventional insulin theory would suggest": "",
  "The gene needs to include bacterial introns based on the conventional understanding of how insulin processes interact in practice": "",
  "The bacteria need to be given human ribosomes when the interaction between insulin and bacteria factors is taken into full account": "",
  "The protein likely needs post-translational modifications (such as disulfide bond formation and cleavage of the signal peptide) that bacteria may not perform correctly": "",
  "Human insulin requires post-translational processing including removal of the signal peptide, cleavage of the C-peptide, and formation of disulfide bonds. Bacteria lack the eukaryotic ER and Golgi machinery for some of these modifications, so additional in vitro processing or use of eukaryotic expression systems may be needed.": "",
  "A student studies a mutation that changes a stop codon (UAG) to a sense codon (UAC, encoding tyrosine). What would be the likely effect on the protein?": "",
  "The protein would be unchanged because stop codons are not part of the reading frame": "",
  "The mutation would prevent transcription of the gene": "",
  "Translation would read through the original stop codon, producing a longer-than-normal protein with extra amino acids at the C-terminus": "",
  "The protein would be truncated and nonfunctional": "",
  "Converting a stop codon to a sense codon (a read-through mutation) would cause the ribosome to continue translating past the normal termination point, adding extra amino acids until the next stop codon is reached. The extended protein may be nonfunctional due to the additional residues.": "",
  "Ribosomes on the rough ER translate mRNAs encoding proteins destined for secretion. A signal sequence at the beginning of the polypeptide directs the ribosome to the ER membrane. If the signal sequence were deleted from the mRNA, where would the protein be synthesized?": "",
  "In the nucleus because conventional analysis of signal suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "On free ribosomes in the cytoplasm, since without the signal sequence, the ribosome-mRNA complex would not be directed to the ER": "",
  "Still on the rough ER, because the ribosome is already bound without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "In the mitochondria, since the relevant signal factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "The signal sequence is recognized by the signal recognition particle (SRP), which directs the ribosome to the ER membrane. Without this signal, the SRP cannot bind, and the ribosome remains free in the cytoplasm, where it completes translation. The protein would stay in the cytoplasm.": "",
  "In an experiment, a researcher adds an mRNA molecule with the sequence 5'-AUGUUUAAAUAG-3' to an in vitro translation system. How many amino acids would the resulting polypeptide contain (excluding the stop)?": "",
  "12": "",
  "Reading in triplets from AUG: AUG (Met) - UUU (Phe) - AAA (Lys) - UAG (stop). The polypeptide would be Met-Phe-Lys, containing 3 amino acids. Translation terminates at the UAG stop codon.": "",
  "A cell biologist observes that after a protein is synthesized on a ribosome, it is tagged with ubiquitin molecules and rapidly degraded by the proteasome. Under what circumstances would a cell deliberately destroy a newly made protein?": "",
  "When the cell has an excess of ribosomes when the interaction between cell and proteasome factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Only when the cell is infected by a virus, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "When the cell is about to undergo DNA replication, as conventional cell theory would suggest": "",
  "When the protein is misfolded, damaged, or no longer needed, the ubiquitin-proteasome pathway targets it for destruction as part of protein quality control": "",
  "The ubiquitin-proteasome pathway is the cell's primary protein quality control system. Misfolded, damaged, or regulatory proteins that are no longer needed are tagged with ubiquitin chains and delivered to the proteasome for degradation, recycling the amino acids.": "",
  "Diphtheria toxin kills cells by modifying elongation factor EF-2, which is essential for translocation of the ribosome along the mRNA. A patient infected with Corynebacterium diphtheriae would experience cell death primarily because:": "",
  "Ribosomes would be unable to move along the mRNA, halting all protein synthesis in affected cells": "",
  "DNA replication would be blocked in all cells": "",
  "mRNA would be degraded before reaching the ribosome": "",
  "The toxin would prevent transcription by inhibiting RNA polymerase": "",
  "Diphtheria toxin ADP-ribosylates EF-2, inactivating it. Without functional EF-2, ribosomes cannot translocate along the mRNA during elongation, and all protein synthesis stops. Without new protein production, cells cannot maintain their functions and die.": ""
}